hints_latex:
Remember the Taylor series for the exponential function:

\begin{align*}
e^{x} = \sum_{k = 0}^{\infty}\frac{x^{k}}{k!}
\end{align*} for all $x$ in the set
of real numbers.

sols_latex:
This question is challenging, but can be solved in an elegant way using
a Taylor series.

To begin with, rewrite the sum as:

\begin{align*}
\sum_{k = 0}^{\infty}\frac{1}{e^{k}k!} &= \sum_{k = 0}^{\infty}\frac{e^{-k}}{k!} = \sum_{k = 0}^{\infty}\frac{(e^{-1})^{k}}{k!}
\end{align*} Next, set \emph{x = e\textsuperscript{-1}} to obtain

\begin{align*}
\sum_{k = 0}^{\infty}\frac{(e^{-1})^{k}}{k!} = \sum_{k = 0}^{\infty}\frac{x^{k}}{k!}
\end{align*}

The last sum, however, is the Taylor series of the exponential function,

\begin{align*}
\sum_{k = 0}^{\infty}\frac{x^{k}}{k!} = e^{x}
\end{align*}

Plugging \emph{x = e\textsuperscript{-1}} back in we find that our final
answer is

\begin{align*}
{\color{blue}\sum_{k = 0}^{\infty}\frac{1}{e^{k}k!} = e^{\left(e^{-1}\right)}}
\end{align*}

sols_raw:
This question is challenging, but can be solved in an elegant way using a &lt;b>Taylor series&lt;/b>.

To begin with, rewrite the sum as:
:&lt;math>
\begin{align}
\sum_{k = 0}^{\infty}\frac{1}{e^{k}k!} &amp;= \sum_{k = 0}^{\infty}\frac{e^{-k}}{k!} = \sum_{k = 0}^{\infty}\frac{(e^{-1})^{k}}{k!}
\end{align}
&lt;/math>
Next, set ''x = e&lt;sup>-1&lt;/sup>'' to obtain

:&lt;math>
\sum_{k = 0}^{\infty}\frac{(e^{-1})^{k}}{k!} = \sum_{k = 0}^{\infty}\frac{x^{k}}{k!}
&lt;/math>

The last sum, however, is the Taylor series of the exponential function,
:&lt;math>
\sum_{k = 0}^{\infty}\frac{x^{k}}{k!} = e^{x}
&lt;/math>

Plugging ''x = e&lt;sup>-1&lt;/sup>'' back in we find that our final answer is
:&lt;math>
{\color{blue}
\sum_{k = 0}^{\infty}\frac{1}{e^{k}k!} = e^{\left(e^{-1}\right)}}
&lt;/math>
